fields.value: Information Search and Restaurant Selection (CAPS-REST CAPS-REST1 CAPS-REST2 CAPS-ASEARCH and CAPS-BSEARCH modules)

dsDescriptionValue.value:
Inferences about the Rs decision process will be based on the search pattern evidenced by the R in a decision task. Major variables will be variability of search and search pattern. A compensatory model would be indicated by an interdimensional, constant pattern (linear model) or an interdimensional, constant pattern (additive difference). Compensatory models imply the search for and use of a constant number of cues for each interdimensional, variable (conjunctive and intradimensional, variab le (EBA elimination by aspects). Noncompensatory models are indicated by the interactive use of cues (a low score on the dimension cannot be compensated for by a high score on another dimension, causing the alternative to be eliminated). It is hypothesized that Rs will be more likely to use compensatory models when they believe that they are working with others than when they believe they are working alone.

The task is adapted from one used by Robert S. Billings and Stephen A. Marcus in Measures of Compensatory and Noncompensatory Models of Decision Behavior: Process Tracing versus Policy Capturing, Organizational Behavior and Human Performance 31,331-352. The Billings and Marcus Design did not employ the group/alone condition and their task was not administered by the computer.

The task presents the R with a choice among a number of restaurants (Billings used apartments), each of whic h is described on four dimensions (each dimension having three values).

Experimental Conditions: For this project, Rs will be assigned to one of four treatment conditions. Otherwise, this is a within-subjects design, so all Rs will get all four experimental treatments. In all treatments, Rs are asked to search the information in an 18 X 4 matrix, where there are 4 attributes (price, quality, location, and service), and 18 restaurants. Each attribute has three possible values, so each restaurant is described by one of 81 possible combinations of the values on the four attributes. The actual pattern of the values to be displayed for each restaurant will be determined via random selection from a set of 54 patterns, chosen from the 81 possible patterns so that they make up an incomplete factorial (or two sets of 27, which constitute an incomplete factorial). The sets of 54 are used in REST1. The 18 patterns not used in REST1 are used in REST2.

Respondents see a matrix with restaurant names listed down the side on the screen and attribute types across the top. In each cell is a number indication the row and column number. A message at the bottom of the screen prompts the respondent to enter a cell number in order to see the value for that restaurant as many times as they wish. This goal is to choose the restaurant, which they would most likely go to under the hypothetical situations described. There are four such situations, whi ch comprise the experimental treatment conditions. Each R works under only one of those conditions, and the values displayed, order of attributes, and selections and order of restaurant names will vary from one R to another. Restaurant names will be randomly selected from a list of 81 possible names. Attribute orders will be varied so that each R gets only one of the possible orders, but this will not be confound with condition order.

Restaurant names in file EXPER:RESTNAMES were EMBERS, GRENADIER, BYRON'S, THE HEARTH, HAWKES PUB, LAKESIDE, OLD TOWNE, MAJOR'S, YOUR PLACCE, KNICKER'S, PALM COURT, BLACK RAM, JAKE'S, EMERSON'S, HIGHLANDER, FIR

A similar unit, REST(1,2), was conducted in CAPS/84. Documentation for that unit is minimal. Unit names in CAPS/85 were ASEARCH and BSEARCH. In CAPS/86 they were REST1 and REST2.

See codebook for additional information
